			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>Optimising First-Class Pattern Matching</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JeffSmits.html">Jeff Smits</a>, <a href="../profile/ToineHartman.html">Toine Hartman</a>, <a href="../profile/JesperCockx.html">Jesper Cockx</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567519">10.1145/3567512.3567519</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagM">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The paper focuses on compilation/optimization techniques for first-class pattern matching.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Its contribution is primarily about improving runtime efficiency of compiled pattern matches.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Pattern matching compilation interacts with static analysis/typing constraints in the frontend.
</li></ul></li></ul>
